    "front": "What is commonhold and what problem does it solve?",
    "back": "Commonhold (Commonhold and Leasehold Reform Act 2002) is a form of freehold ownership designed for multi-unit developments (e.g. blocks of flats). Each unit holder owns the freehold of their unit, and the common parts are owned and managed by a commonhold association (a company limited by guarantee of which all unit holders are members). It solves the positive covenant problem — positive obligations (repair, contribute to maintenance) are enforceable against successive unit holders because they bind as part of the commonhold community statement.",
    "details": "The positive covenant problem: at common law, the burden of positive freehold covenants does not run with the land (Rhone v Stephens [1994]). This means flat owners who hold freehold cannot be compelled by covenant to contribute to repairs. The leasehold system avoids this (covenants run in leases) but at the cost of diminishing assets. Commonhold was intended to replace leasehold for flats, but has been rarely used since 2004 due to practical difficulties (lender reluctance, inability to convert existing buildings without unanimous consent). The Law Commission recommended reforms in 2020.",
